Project-local source-backed packages are normal Beanstalk source roots discovered from configured package folders. Each direct child directory becomes an import prefix.

### Configuration

[codeblock, $code("bst"):
    package_folders #= {
        "lib",
    }
]

When `package_folders` is omitted, `/lib` is the default scan folder.

### Directory structure

[codeblock, $code("text"):
    project-root/
    ├── config.bst
    ├── src/
    │   └── #page.bst
    └── lib/
        └── helper/
            ├── #api.bst
            └── utils.bst
]

The direct child folder `lib/helper` becomes the `@helper` package prefix. The package's public surface is controlled by its module root (`#api.bst`).

### Generic hash-root naming

The package root filename after `#` has no semantic role. `#api.bst`, `#mod.bst` and `#page.bst` are all equivalent root spellings for a source-backed package. See @../project-structure/#module-roots (Module roots).

### One root per package module

Each package directory may contain at most one `#*.bst` root file. Two or more hash-root files in one package directory are rejected with `BST-CONFIG-0001`.

### Public surface

Outside importers can only see declarations and grouped re-exports marked public by the package root's `export:` block. Internal implementation files are not public unless the root re-exports them.

### Internal child files

Files without `#` in the package directory are normal source files within the package module. They are hidden from cross-prefix imports unless the package root re-exports them.

### Custom scan roots

`package_folders` accepts one string or a collection of strings. Each configured folder becomes a scan root. Its direct child directories become import prefixes.

### Duplicate or ambiguous prefixes

Duplicate package folders are rejected. Absolute paths and paths containing `..` are rejected. Nested paths such as `lib/helpers` are rejected. Each entry must be a direct folder name relative to the project root.

### Project-local packages compile as Beanstalk source

Project-local source-backed packages are not opaque bindings. They are normal Beanstalk source files compiled through the same frontend pipeline.

### Imported package roots do not produce routes

A source-backed package root is imported rather than activated as an HTML route. Its top-level runtime body and page fragments remain inactive in the consuming project, even when authored content exists. It exports declarations but produces no HTML artifact. See @../project-structure/#html-routing-and-artifacts (HTML routing and artifacts).

### Origin and backing are separate

Configured package-folder children are ProjectLocal packages backed by Beanstalk source. `@html` is also source-backed but has Builder origin. `@core/math` and `@web/canvas` are binding-backed packages with Core and Builder origins respectively. See @#package-origins-and-backing (Package origins and backing).

### Related concepts

- For module root rules see @../project-structure/#module-roots (Module roots).
- For the export block see @../project-structure/#public-api (Public API).
- For import path resolution see @#import-paths (Import paths).
